Avoid the unrealistic prices!  Have 1,000 shipped to your home for $238.95 + 26.34 UPS shipping.  Roughly $266!  Check out other 9mm brands as well as other calibers at gunbot.net.  As the image shows, that's one of the vendors listed at gunbot.net under 9mm.  That's Ammunition To Go's price.  My post here is showing the web site is listing that ammo and they will ship it to your house. Don't reply to me, I don't sell ammo. I'm just helping others by showing alternatives to local high prices. 

I suggest gunbot.net or ammoseek.com to find the cheapest sellers. Sure, some local sellers run some great special sales.  If in a pinch when local are low, just pick the caliber you're shopping for first, then sort by price per round, then pick the brand you want, amount, and price. Click on the link. It will take you to that vendor's site. I posted a photo as an example. You can filter out steel case and reloads as well at gunbot.net.  By the way, some ammo sites are definitely cheaper than others on shipping costs.  It was nuts during the shortage, it seems to be getting better now.

I hope this is helpful.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Taurus PT99 AFS, mags, holster
postcontent:
CAUTION: HONEST AD! 

For trade: Taurus PT99 AFS 9mm

Hey guys and gals:

I recently lost out on a smokin deal to get a 1911 and have been kicking myself since. 

It is a stainless steel slide/nickel-plated (I believe) framed 9mm patterned after the Beretta M9 style if pistols. Does not have the tactical rails. Comes with five total magazines: 4-15 rounders and 1-30 rounder. Also comes with a Fobus holster (not pictured... nothing special). 

The good: Gun is in great shape visually, and very good shape functionally. I've personally never had any issues with it except with one finicky mag made for both Taurus and Beretta pistols.

The bad: This is the line from Taurus that uses adjustable rear sights. A common problem is that they do not hold up to the recoil of the action and eventually break. This one is no different. The securing nut for the windage screw is stripped (got it that way) and a detent for the adjustment is missing. I have gotten it to where the blade no longer moves and feels fairly stable, but have not yet gotten to range test it. Replacement rear sight assemblies are also fairly hard to find. A gunsmith actually recommended I find slide center and "Loc-Tite the piss out of it." Maybe some other time, lol.

The ugly: Nothing! I think it's a damn sexy gun! I WOULD keep it... but the 1911 bug is rooted in my veins! 

Looking for an entry level 1911, like an ATI, S.A.M., or RIA (to be similar in value). Really would prefer military style (plain grip safety, 5in. barrel, parkerized/blued finish, etc.). I can include 9mm ammo if needed to seal the deal, but cash reserves are too low to offer anything like that (I'd probably just buy one new from CTD otherwise).

Might (heavy emphasis on might) also possibly be intersted in a nicer semi-auto .22lr pistol to plink with and train new shooters.

If gun sits waiting on a trade, would sell for $450 (can include ammo at below retail for extra cash)
Thanks! Don't worry, I'm done now.

title: For Sale:  WWII 1940 Lee-Enfield Military Rifle
postcontent:
WWII 1940 Lee-Enfield Military Rifle,.303 caliber Enfield rifle, Mark III, Serial # 14XXX on both receiver and underside of wood. Crown over “G.R.” = George Rex (George VI, King of England during WWII), manufacture date “1940” + “Sht.L.E” = Short Lee Enfield (short magazine) + star + “III.” =  Mark III, (made 1915-1953). Manufacturer’s mark “M” = Maltby, Royal Ordinance Factory in Maltby, Yorkshire, “BSA” under stacked rifles on bolt = Birmingham Small Arms logo, a number of proof marks and inspector’s marks on metal and wood.

History: At the outbreak of WWII, BSA was the only factory producing rifles in the UK. During the Battle of Britain in 1940 the BSA factory was bombed several times by the Luftwaffe, destroying the machine shops and stopping rifle production.  The British government and BSA immediately established “shadow factories” throughout Britain to increase arms production in areas less vulnerable to German air attacks. The Royal Ordinance Factory was then established at Maltby and produced Enfield rifles. I believe this rifle was one of those produced early in the war during the Battle of Britain.

*Many of the available Enfield rifles are either non-military commercial rifles made for export, or unserviceable arms “sold out of the service” to the civilian market. All of these will have civilian or export markings, obliterated proof marks, or non-war time dates. Others were cut down, “sporterized” and converted to hunting rifles. This is an original 1940 WWII battle rifle. The rifle of course shows use, but everything functions properly. (I purchased this rifle privately as a collectible from an older gentleman I know, who told me he purchased it in the early 1970s from the WWII vet who brought it back in 1945.)

Will not ship, face-to face sale only.

The MAS Modèle 36 was a military bolt action rifle. First adopted in 1936 by France and intended to replace the Berthier and Lebel series of service rifles, it saw service long past the World War II period. It was manufactured by Manufacture d'Armes de Saint-Étienne (MAS), one of several government-owned arms factories in France. Because production was initiated late in 1937, not enough MAS-36 rifles were available to arm French infantry when the war broke out in September 1939. Mass production finally caught up after World War II and MAS-36 rifles became widely used in service during the First Indochina War, the Algerian War and the Suez Crisis. Production ceased in 1952.
